## codegraph

codegraph integration is **strictly opt-in per project**. A project participates only when **both** conditions hold:

1. the project note's YAML frontmatter has `code_graph: true`, AND
2. `<repo-path>/.codegraph/codegraph.db` exists in the repository resolved from the project's `local` property (the codegraph index has been built).

When either condition is false, treat the project as if codegraph did not exist: do not read the index, do not run `codegraph` commands, do not suggest running them. No skill, workflow, or post-edit hook may invoke codegraph on a non-opted-in project.

When both conditions hold (project opted in):
- Prefer the codegraph MCP tools (`codegraph_explore` first, then `codegraph_search`, `codegraph_callers`, `codegraph_callees`, `codegraph_impact`, `codegraph_files`, `codegraph_status`) or the CLI (`codegraph query`, `codegraph callers|callees|impact`, `codegraph status`) before broad grep/glob searches over that repo.
- For cross-module "how does X relate to Y" questions, prefer `codegraph_explore` naming the symbols that span the flow — or `codegraph callers|callees|impact "<symbol>"` — over grep.
- **Never run `codegraph init`, `codegraph index`, `codegraph sync`, or any index-mutating codegraph command automatically.** Refreshing the index is the sole responsibility of [[skills/task-planning/SKILL|task-planning]] step 10 (`codegraph sync`), which runs only against the **main checkout** (the path from `local`). Do not refresh the index from `task-implementation`, `task-finalize`, `task-review`, `address-pr-findings`, or any post-edit step. Read-only MCP/CLI queries are always fine.
- **Never run any index-mutating `codegraph` command inside a git worktree.** The `.codegraph/` index belongs to the main checkout only; worktree directories (sibling folders matching `<repo>-<branch-slug>`) must stay free of `.codegraph/`. If a worktree contains a `.codegraph/` folder from a past mistake, ignore it and do not refresh it; flag it to the user for cleanup.
